Men have invented and uſe a Variety of artificial Methods to inſpire themſelves and one another with Courage: The Beat of Drums, the Blaſt of Trumpets, and Shouting for the Battle; theſe may ſomewhat rouſe the Spirits, and breed a Kind of brutal Courage, a wild and mad Fury, like that of the War-Horſe;
               Job. xxxix. 21,— 
               who faith among the Trumpets, Ha, ha, goeth on to meet the armed Men, mocketh at Fear, and is not affrighted; neither turneth back from the Sword; ſwalloweth the Ground with Fierceneſs and Rage, and ruſhes into the Battle. This is falſe Courage, purely a mechanical Buſineſs: It hurries Men on precipitately into the Mouth of Danger, without Thought or Wit, Conſideration or Conduct; and often leaves them when they have the greateſt Need. It degenerates into Fear and Cowardiſe. It is a ſudden Fluſh of the Spirits, which quickly goes off, like the Crackling of Thorns under a Pot, makes a great Noiſe and Blaze, but is ſoon over.
